article.description:
Lisa Leslie scored 24 points to lead the
playoff-bound Los Angeles Sparks to a 76-59 victory over the
Minnesota Lynx on Sunday night.
article.headline: Sparks feed playoff fire with easy victory over Lynx
article.linkText: Sparks feed playoff fire with easy victory over Lynx
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Lisa Leslie scored 24 points to lead the
playoff-bound Los Angeles Sparks to a 78-59 victory over the
Minnesota Lynx on Sunday night.

Murriel Page added 14 points and Doneeka Hodges-Lewis had a
career-high nine assists for the Sparks (25-9), who enter the
playoffs with the WNBA's best home record at 15-2. They had already
clinched the Western Conference division title.

Los Angeles will open the playoffs Friday at Seattle.

Leslie averaged 20 points in the regular season for the first
time in her long career, finishing the campaign at 20.6 per game.

"I really wasn't aware of what was going on points-wise until
the end," she said. "I mean, it would've been kind of sad if I
missed it by a whole point."

Sparks coach Joe Bryant knew what was at stake for Leslie, and
he wanted her to score from the perimeter to avoid injury.

"These opportunities only come once in a while," he said.
"Down the stretch, everything was jumpers for Lisa. We planned it
that way, instead of going inside and getting banged up."

Rookie Seimone Augustus had 11 points to set a team record for
most points in a season for the Lynx (10-24), who lost nine of
their final 10 games to finish with the worst record in team
history. Augustus scored 744 points, bettering the mark of 739 set
by Katie Smith in 2001.

Svetlana Abrosimova added 10 points and nine rebounds.

"We have to become a much better defensive team than we've been
in the past," Lynx interim coach Carolyn Jenkins said. "If you
look at the playoff teams, they're able to defend night in and
night out."

Los Angeles dominated the second quarter to build a 46-25
halftime lead. Page scored 10 points and grabbed six rebounds in
the period, and Lisa Willis added eight points.

Minnesota failed to score a basket in the final 6:05 of the
first half.
